The skeptic in me didn't want to like Tartine Bakery. It was the one place everyone recommended. Would it be overrated, overhyped? Nope, it was solidly the best meal I had in San Francisco. I woke up early to stand in line at 7:15am on a random Thursday. There was already a line, but it moves fast thanks to the efficiency of the staff. I ordered three things- the croque monsieur, the chocolate croissant, and a latte. The croque monsieur comes out on a big open faced bread and is made by angels. It's very creamy and full of flavor. The chocolate croissant is buttery without being overly and has the perfect ratio to dough to chocolate. The dough is very good too. The latte was the best I had in the city. The cafe itself is beautiful inside and the staff friendly. It's definitely a noteworthy place to visit.

Been here a few times and had a variety of things to try. The tea cake is the only thing worth getting. I don't understand the hype. The lines are ridiculously long. And after that ridiculous line, Their cakes and baked goods are just meh to ok. Nothing stands out. There are other quality bakeries that would shame this place. Check out The Neighbor Bakehouse. Best bakery in the city. Only thing this place has is the location since it is so close to Dolores Park. Thanks, but no thanks. Seriously not worth it and overrated.

So I popped into Tartine before leaving to Sonoma and spent $45 on assorted breakfast pastries. I regret nothing about this decision, becuase outside of France I have never experienced croissants like these. Holy cow, believe the hype. Tartine is GOAT. For the years I have visited SF for work, I have been told about these ham and cheese croissants. But never have I ever visited Tartine. Of course, this was the first thing I had to order. I also ordered some sort of cheese bread. In addition to these savories - I went for the almond croissant and the chocolate one too because I mean...when at Tartine. I was able to try the Croque Monsieur, the bread pudding, and the morning bun. In summary - leave no carb behind at Tartine. You will not be sorry.

Ahh, the smell of it! When visiting the city, this is a must-stop. We grab the occasional vegan delight that they have on hand, and snatch up a few loves of bread to take home with us. They smell of their baked goods fills the corner of Guerrero, and beyond. Busy, boisterous, and extremely crowded, this isn't the place for patrons who are claustrophobic. We've usually stayed close by and watched the lines for a break in the crowds. If you haven't tried Tartine, what are you waiting for?

We came in for early evening dessert on a weeknight, upon my friend's recommendation. It was closing soon so the selection wasn't at 100%. I tried the Orange Sesame Teacake because it sounded unique and I had never had anything like that before. It was covered in sesame seeds and I could taste both the orange and the tea. The small hot chocolate helped accompany the teacake. My friend had the Almond Pistachio Cranberry. I found the prices to be quite expensive ($5.25 for each cake, $4.00 for the hot chocolate, plus surcharge), but I also don't spend all of my time in San Francisco. When you order, they give you the cake/pastry directly and call you for the hot drinks. They have water available in plastic cups. You are strongly encouraged to bus your table. After a second, we figured out where everything goes. If you go back toward the cash register, there is an arrangement of bins where you can sort your trash.

I love a good bakery as much as anyone, but Tartine is overrated. When I first came in, I was impressed by the variety. They have multiple varieties of coffee, bread, and sandwiches, in addition to pastries. However, this variety is completely counteracted by the price. Each item here was heavily marked up and, quite frankly, it wasn't worth it. I tried the chocolate croissant and the pumpkin bread. Both were good--I don't have any complaints. However, when you pay $6 for a croissant, you expect to be wowed.

Honestly, the only times I've ever visited Tartine Bakery was when friends visiting San Francisco wanted to go. As a SF native, I'm put off by the long lines for an ok-bakery, as there are so many other local shops that are cheaper and have richer flavors. The shop itself it very small and seats maybe at most 25 people. Therefore, when people just want to order the pastries, a long queue forms and pools outside the door. Thus, by proxy and sheep effect, more and more people come to see what the commotion is about. However, for this particular visit, the line was empty, so I decided to test my luck in seeing if my perception would change. It was eh. Got a Double Pain Au Chocolate, and it looks so pretty because of the flakey crust and distinct layers. I expected it to be a bit more moist and delectable on the inside, but it was dry all the way through, and the chocolate was a bit chalky. I think what lends itself to its hype and popularity is by being so close to Mission Delores Park, and being informally considered a tourist destination as a result. You can see from the multitudes of positive reviews that it appeals to a specific demographic as well, so it can get away with being overhyped and overpriced. Although not my favorite bakery in the city, I know that I'll probably be coming back the next time I play SF tourguide.

We got the coconut cream tart and the banana cream tart. Both topped with a light layer of cream that sits on top a thicker than condensed milk/heavier/sweeter layer of inner cream. The crust is flaky, yet sturdy enough to hold everything together, and is lined with a layer of chocolate. The banana cream tart contained chilled banana slices. Other than that, the cream and crust was the same as the coconut cream tart so the banana was not overpowering! The coconut cream tart was topped with lots of coconut shavings, while the banana cream tart was topped with chocolate savings. In terms of sweetness, on a 1-10 scale, I'd give it a 6-7 so it's medium sweet (not a tart tart) and each can enjoy his/her own!

The weekend I went they had this apple crumble that was vegan and it was tasty but nothing I would go out of my way for. The wait to get in is long so you better be prepared to wait outside.

It's a scoop of lemon blueberry cake in a mug. Soft, spongey, with a little tanginess. Overall, would highly recommend as well. Overall, I had a pretty good experience & loved what they had to offer. It is a little on the pricier side; however, I haven't found a place that does it cheaper AND better. Will definitely come back to try their other items.

My boyfriend and I heard about Tartine Bakery from a TV show - not even a food or travel related show but a comic book show (Titans on the DC Network). The particular episode we watched mentioned that Tartine in the Mission was the best bakery in the City, so we went out of our way to test that theory. Well, they had it right. I 100% agree that Tartine is legit, and the food is excellent! We arrived at Tartine Bakery around 9am on a Sunday. The place was already very busy, and the line was out the door. It moved fairly quickly, however. We only waited for about 15 minutes to finally order, and it also helped that there were 3 servers managing the queue. Tartine had an assortment of tarts, cakes, pastries, and savory items. We had to try a little bit of everything, so we got the morning bun, chocolate croissants, brioche bread pudding, lemon tart, and croque monsieur to go. My boyfriend and I shared the croque monsieur. Tartine had two kinds for croque monseiurs that morning: a cheese and a mushroom. I got the cheese, which was definitely different from traditional croque monsieur. I was expecting to have ham in it, but then I understood that the fromage blanc was the replacement for the ham. It was still very good and surprisingly filling. The brioche bread pudding was delicious. It was topped with sliced peaches and some type of small berry (currents maybe?) in syrup. The look and feel of the brioche was eggy, so it reminded me a lot of a flan. Admittedly I haven't had the chance to try the morning bun, chocolate croissants, and lemon tart yet. I have no doubts though that they will be amazing based on croque monsieur and bread pudding I had the pleasure of trying first!

Chocolate Croissant! Oh my Napoleon... they're the best! Save the trip to Paris and come here instead. They have everything from desserts, cakes, croissants, morning buns, bread and paninis. It's like an adult candy store. Today (afternoon) I stopped in for a quick morning bun, chocolate croissant and a mocha latte. I didn't even bother to sit down as every seat was taken, and rightfully so, this place always has a line, always packed But I swear it's worth it. If you see open seats ask the people around you if you can sit, everyone is usually nice enough to share the tables. Tip: They will only heat up your buns/croissants upon request. Don't be shy, he staff are very helpful and kind. Also, they sell out fast, of everything. So come early in the morning. If you're going to grab a coffee/latte/mocha they're delicious but a bit costly for the size. But again, it's worth it. Lastly, I highly recommend trying the paninis. They're super crispy and delicious.

I went to Tartine on a Saturday morning and expected a line out the door, which it was. It took about 30 minutes between getting in line and checking out. I ordered 2 things: the morning bun and the banana cream tart. Both were AMAZING. Some of the best pastries I've had in my entire life! The morning bun was the perfect flavor and had a great flakey texture. The banana cream tart crust was a little too hard making it hard to eat. But as far as taste goes, I was in heaven. You need both of these! But I'm sure everything else at Tartine is just as delicious. Will definitely go back to try more

I got there pretty early, maybe around 9am. Waited around 15-20 min. The almond croissant and morning bun were great. Fresh, fine layering, delicious fillings. The bread pudding completely confused me. Let's put it this way: combining bread and custard together in varying ratios will net you different products. More bread with just enough custard to moisten gets you french toast. Add more custard and you get bread pudding. The "bread pudding" here is waaaaay on the custard end of the spectrum. Think of it more as a custard with some bread in it to add some substance. It eats very much as a custard as there is no bite to it whatsoever. And then to put cooked berries on it makes it even MORE water logged. That being said, custard with berries is tasty, but just manage your expectations when you order it.

This place had been hyped up to me for a while even before I moved to SF. I always wanted to try it but often when walking by but got intimidated by the long line. I've been here twice since then - the first time I got the lemon tart and it's soooo good. Very lemony, strong flavors, and the tart itself is soft and buttery. It's also beautiful with the lil flowers on top. The second time I got the frangipane tart because it looked beautiful with the dogs on top cut. I wasn't as much into it as the lemon tart though because it was a bit dry and not too sweet. Probably just didn't fit my tastes. When you're waiting in line you stand by the window of al their pastries and just want to order everything because it's all so beautiful. I'll definitely keep coming back here to try more things.

As a sourdough bread aficionado, I visited this spot as a major aspect of my bread journey. Words can't do equity to the enchantment of their sourdough! I can hardly wait to be back once more. They work superbly with their baked goods and cakes as well! The interminable long queue of clients is there for a valid justification!

I'm so freakin' excited to find tartine in LA! We have never lived in San Francisco and have only been twice but each time made a point to go to tartine to get their amazing breads and pastries. Anyways, this location has ample parking and is nice and new. I hear they serve brunch on the restaurant side but recommend reservations. I found the online info a bit confusing so here's the deal. On one side you will find a bakery similar to the SanFran location. Here you can pick up breads, pastries, coffee, and juices to take home or eat on site. On the other side there is a full service restaurant. There is seating inside and outside in a nice covered patio. Finally made it to the bread mecca. Though the line curls around the street, it moves pretty fast, and it's a pleasant wait as you're blasted with delicious bready smells the whole time. Tried two breakfast items - savory scone and an enormous black pepper gougère - both were fabulous. The real star was the loaf we took home, one of their combo white/wheat - unconscionably moist, glistens when you cut into it. Perfection.

Came here with a roomie on a Sunday afternoon at around 2pm after going to the Manufactory awhile back. We waited about 30 minutes, as the line never seems to stop wrapping around the store (went faster than it looked though!). We each got a panini and then split some desserts. I ordered the Humboldt Fog Goat Cheese sandwich ($15), which was basically an elevated grilled cheese. It was super good, though I do wish there was meat it in because the cheese was a bit too heavy for me. My roommate got the ($17), Spicy Turkey that looked AMAZING with the pesto. She also said it was pretty good. My roommate also got a latte that she said was good. Both portions were HUGE and we had to take some of the sandwiches home. For dessert, we split the Banana Cream Tart (4"- $9) and the Morning Bun ($5). I favored the creamy banana tart, which was so decadent, yet light, with the chocolate shavings. The morning bun was also good, but I'm not a huge fan of the candied orange flavor, so I preferred the tart. Overall, while I like the Manufactory setting better, I actually preferred the food at the bakery better. I will definitely be back!

This is one of our favorite bakery stops when in the city in the morning! Even right at opening, there is a line out the door. Parking isn't the greatest which is not at all their fault but as they get popular and rent etc goes up, so does the price of these delectables. Must haves - morning bun with candied orange in between the layers Pain At Jambon with Jalapeño ( but any are pretty darn good) Teacake slices (chocolate and almond poppy lemon) and even the Crumb cake is yummy! The list goes on and on - if you want banana cream tarts - they are usually avail an hour after opening so it's super fresh. Can't ever really leave this place without spending at least $75 for the 4 of us! Can't do this everyday but worth it for the once in awhile - definitely a must try if you haven't ever had it before!

    If you're going to grab a coffee/latte/mocha they're delicious but a bit costly for the size. But again, it's worth it. Lastly, I highly recommend trying the paninis. They're super crispy and delicious.

    I got there pretty early, maybe around 9am. Waited around 15-20 min. The almond croissant and morning bun were great. Fresh, fine layering, delicious fillings.

    The bread pudding completely confused me. Let's put it this way: combining bread and custard together in varying ratios will net you different products. More bread with just enough custard to moisten gets you french toast. Add more custard and you get bread pudding.

    The "bread pudding" here is waaaaay on the custard end of the spectrum. Think of it more as a custard with some bread in it to add some substance. It eats very much as a custard as there is no bite to it whatsoever. And then to put cooked berries on it makes it even MORE water logged. That being said, custard with berries is tasty, but just manage your expectations when you order it.

    I'm so freakin' excited to find tartine in LA!
    We have never lived in San Francisco and have only been twice but each time made a point to go to tartine to get their amazing breads and pastries.

    Anyways, this location has ample parking and is nice and new. I hear they serve brunch on the restaurant side but recommend reservations.  

    I found the online info a bit confusing so here's the deal.

    On one side you will find a bakery similar to the SanFran location. Here you can pick up breads, pastries, coffee, and juices to take home or eat on site.

    On the other side there is a full service restaurant. There is seating inside and outside in a nice covered patio. As of the writing of this review I understand the focus of the restaurant is shifting from american food to pizza.

    Tartine can be pricey but is high quality and delicious!

    We each got a panini and then split some desserts. I ordered the Humboldt Fog Goat Cheese sandwich ($15), which was basically an elevated grilled cheese. It was super good, though I do wish there was meat it in because the cheese was a bit too heavy for me. My roommate got the ($17), Spicy Turkey that looked AMAZING with the pesto. She also said it was pretty good. My roommate also got a latte that she said was good. Both portions were HUGE and we had to take some of the sandwiches home.

    For dessert, we split the Banana Cream Tart (4"- $9) and the Morning Bun ($5). I favored the creamy banana tart, which was so decadent, yet light, with the chocolate shavings. The morning bun was also good, but I'm not a huge fan of the candied orange flavor, so I preferred the tart.

    Overall, while I like the Manufactory setting better, I actually preferred the food at the bakery better. I will definitely be back!
